This paper discusses the design and implementation of a framework for anonymous communication systems using JavaScript. The paper addresses potential attacks against the system and ethical issues related to its deployment, which are typical concerns in the field of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the practicality of the system, which involves generating dummy messages for mix-nets and DC-nets, which are topics related to distributed computing (cs.DC). The use of JavaScript in the framework suggests a focus on programming languages and compilers (cs.PL), and the framework's potential for increasing anonymity sets suggests a focus on cryptography (cs.CY). Finally, the paper discusses the architecture of the system, which is a topic related to software engineering (cs.SE).
